I'm annoyed with Dr. Siegel.

If a vaccine doesn't expose you to the antigen in question, it's not a vaccine.

If people vaccinated against one antigen get infected with a different antigen, it cannot be considered a breakthrough case.

If a shot is given to generate circulating antibodies that have a neutralizing effect on an antigen but does not expose someone to that antigen and then generate immunological memory of that antigen, it's not a booster shot.

It might confer some level of protection from severe disease, but it doesn't generate immunity.

We update the flu shot every year because of mutations.

Yet here we are, recommending "booster shots" of a vaccine that only immunizes people against an already extinct variant. And we're going to need them every six months, as our circulating antibodies degrade over time. And those antibodies, even when circulating, are only 1/3 as effective at neutralizing delta as they were at neutralizing the original.

Unless omicron proves to be as or more virulent than the original variant, I'll wait for an updated vaccine, thank you very much. And even if it does, I'll wait to see what my chances are as someone who had COVID and now has arrhythmia and interstitial lung disease almost certainly from exposure to the spike protein.
